  "text": "Django migration squashing compliance is implemented across several key files in the django/db/migrations module. The squashmigrations.py command (django/core/management/commands/squashmigrations.py) serves as the squash migration generator, creating new migration files with a replaces attribute that tracks which migrations are being replaced. The Migration class (django/db/migrations/migration.py) defines the replaces attribute that stores the list of migration names a squash migration replaces. The MigrationLoader class (django/db/migrations/loader.py) handles replaced-migrations tracking through the _resolve_replaced_migration_keys() method which recursively resolves replaced migration keys, and the replace_migration() method which processes the actual replacement logic. The build_graph() method in loader.py orchestrates the entire graph construction including the application of replacements, while all_replaced_applied() implements the squash completeness check by verifying that all migrations replaced by a squash migration have been applied. The check_consistent_history() method validates that no applied migrations have unapplied dependencies, with special handling for squashed migrations. The MigrationGraph class (django/db/migrations/graph.py) implements the dependency graph validation after squashing through remove_replaced_nodes() which updates the graph structure when replaced migrations are removed, and remove_replacement_node() which handles the inverse operation. The validate_consistency() method ensures no dummy nodes (orphaned dependencies) remain in the graph. Finally, the MigrationExecutor class (django/db/migrations/executor.py) calls check_replacements() to mark replacement migrations as applied when all their replaced migrations are applied, and the MigrationWriter class (django/db/migrations/writer.py) handles serializing and writing the replaces attribute to migration files."
}

